  "prompt": "If someone launders money, do they break the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained funds appear legitimate by concealing their true source. This typically involves a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers to obscure the origin of the money, often by moving it through legitimate businesses or financial institutions.\n\nIn most countries, money laundering is a serious criminal offense. It is punishable by significant fines, imprisonment, and other penalties. Laws against money laundering are designed to combat organized crime, terrorism financing, tax evasion, and other illicit activities. Key legislation includes:\n\n- **United States:** The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA), the USA PATRIOT Act, and the Money Laundering Control Act (part of the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986).\n- **International:** The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n\nIf someone launders money, they are breaking the law and can face severe legal consequences.",
